			</div>

			<div class="example">
			    <span>7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0</span>
			</div>


	</li> <br>

	<li>Multiply each bit by 2^(its digit number) <br>

		ex.<br>

		(1 x 2^7) = 128<br>

		(0 x 2^6) = 0<br>

		(1 x 2^5) = 32<br>

		(1 x 2^4) = 16<br>

		(0 x 2^3) = 0<br>

		(0 x 2^2) = 0<br>

		(1 x 2^1) = 2<br>

		(0 x 2^0) = 0

	</li> <br>

	<li>Sum the results from the last step. This is the decimal form of the original binary number! <br>

	ex. 128 + 0 + 32 + 16 + 0 + 0 + 2 + 0 = 178</li>
</ol><br>

<h3>Decimal to Binary</h3>

<ol>
	<li>Repeatedly divide the decimal number by 2 until the quotient is 0, keeping track of the remainder each time. <br>

		ex. 42<br><br>

		42 / 2 = 21 R <b>0</b><br>

		21 / 2 = 10 R <b>1</b><br>

		10 / 2 = 5 R <b>0</b><br>

		5 / 2 = 2 R <b>1</b><br>

		2 / 2 = 1 R <b>0</b><br>

		1 / 2 = 0 R <b>1</b>

	</li> <br>

	<li>Append the remainders, starting with the remainder from the last division as the leftmost bit and the remainder from the first division as the rightmost bit. This is your binary value.<br>

		ex. 101010</li>
</ol><br>

